<br>
- I have to totally disagree. I think Legends has marked the height of EQ. You just know a company is doing well when they release specialized service for their more wealthy customers. The amount of uproar they got because of this, yet still went ahead with it, suggests to me that they really aren't worried. A game with 400,000 subscribers, and growing weekly. Why the hell should they be worried?<br>
In a way, however, I do think one aspect of the quote was right. It has marked the beginning of EQ... back then. With the major creators of EverQuest moving on and a new influx of players, I think it's marked a change in EverQuest - from what it once was, to what it will be now. Yes, I do think it is more of a cash cow now (hence Legends), I think it's becomming more commercial (what product doesn't when it succeeds?), and I do think there's room for improvement. However, this is the human race. We thrive from stuff like this.<br>
I'd like to give two thumbs up for Verant for creating such a great comodoty fetish product. And I'd also like to give them  two middle fingers for eating my social life. <p>Halo 57th Beguiler<br>
